# Task: Add Layered Shadow System

## Overview

Create a systematic shadow system with multiple elevation levels. Shadows create depth hierarchy—higher elements cast larger, softer shadows.

## Background

In dark themes, shadows work differently than light themes:
- Can't rely on dark shadows alone (already dark)
- Need combination of dark shadow + subtle glow
- Layer multiple shadows for realism
- Keep shadows subtle—dark themes are already atmospheric

## Implementation Details

### Shadow Tokens

```css
:root {
  /* Base shadows (elevation levels) */
  --shadow-xs: 0 1px 2px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2);
  --shadow-sm: 0 2px 4px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2),
               0 1px 2px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.15);
  --shadow-md: 0 4px 8px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2),
               0 2px 4px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.15);
  --shadow-lg: 0 8px 16px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.25),
               0 4px 8px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.15);
  --shadow-xl: 0 16px 32px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3),
               0 8px 16px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2);

  /* Glow shadows (for interactive elements) */
  --shadow-glow-sm: 0 0 10px var(--glow-primary);
  --shadow-glow-md: 0 0 20px var(--glow-primary);
  --shadow-glow-lg: 0 0 30px var(--glow-primary);

  /* Combined shadows (elevation + glow) */
  --shadow-card: var(--shadow-md);
  --shadow-card-hover: var(--shadow-lg), var(--shadow-glow-sm);
  --shadow-button-hover: var(--shadow-sm), var(--shadow-glow-sm);

  /* Inset shadows (for pressed states) */
  --shadow-inset: inset 0 2px 4px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3);
}
```

### Application

```css
.card {
  box-shadow: var(--shadow-card);
  transition: box-shadow 0.2s ease;
}

.card:hover {
  box-shadow: var(--shadow-card-hover);
}

.btn:hover {
  box-shadow: var(--shadow-button-hover);
}

.btn:active {
  box-shadow: var(--shadow-inset);
}

/* Header when scrolled */
.site-header.scrolled {
  box-shadow: var(--shadow-lg);
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Shadow tokens defined at multiple elevation levels
- [ ] Glow shadows available for interactive elements
- [ ] Combined shadows for common use cases
- [ ] Shadows are subtle, not overpowering
- [ ] Transitions are smooth when shadow changes
- [ ] Performance is good (shadows can be expensive)

## Files to Modify

- `assets/css/style.scss` - Add shadow tokens and apply

## Testing

- Verify shadows create visible but subtle depth
- Check transitions are smooth
- Test on lower-powered devices for performance

# Task: Style Lists

## What
Apply custom styling to unordered and ordered lists with neon green accents.

## Why
- Lists are used extensively (skills, deliverables, etc.)
- Custom bullets reinforce the theme
- Proper spacing improves readability
- Default bullets are boring

## Design Specification

### Unordered Lists
- Custom bullet: Neon green
- Options: `•` character, `>` character, or CSS ::marker
- Adequate line-height and margin between items

### Ordered Lists
- Numbers in neon green
- Same spacing as unordered

## Implementation

### CSS
```scss
ul, ol {
  padding-left: 1.5rem;
  margin: 1rem 0;

  li {
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
    line-height: 1.6;
  }
}

ul {
  list-style: none;

  li {
    position: relative;
    padding-left: 1rem;

    &::before {
      content: '>';
      position: absolute;
      left: 0;
      color: var(--color-primary);
      font-family: var(--font-heading);
    }
  }
}

// Alternative using ::marker (simpler but less control)
// ul li::marker {
//   color: var(--color-primary);
// }

ol {
  li::marker {
    color: var(--color-primary);
    font-family: var(--font-heading);
  }
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Unordered lists have neon green bullets/markers
- [ ] Ordered lists have neon green numbers
- [ ] Spacing between items is comfortable
- [ ] Nested lists work correctly
- [ ] Indentation is appropriate

# Overview

Optimize the mobile experience to be truly excellent—not just "responsive" but purpose-built for touch. Mobile users are often 50%+ of traffic; they deserve an experience designed specifically for their context.

## Background & Justification

Most "responsive" sites just scale down desktop designs. World-class mobile experiences (Stripe, Linear on mobile, Arc) are fundamentally different:
- Touch targets sized for fingers, not cursors
- Interactions designed for touch, not hover
- Navigation patterns optimized for thumb reach
- Performance optimized for mobile constraints

Current state: Our site is responsive (scales down) but not mobile-optimized. Touch targets may be too small. No mobile-specific navigation pattern. Hover states don't work on touch.

## Goals

1. Audit and fix touch targets (minimum 48x48px)
2. Implement a proper mobile navigation pattern (hamburger menu)
3. Optimize typography for mobile reading
4. Adapt animations for mobile (simpler, shorter)
5. Add touch-specific feedback (tap highlights, active states)

## Technical Approach

### Touch Target Audit
- Minimum size: 48x48px (exceeds Apple's 44px guideline)
- Minimum gap between targets: 8px
- Check: buttons, nav links, footer links, any interactive element

```css
.btn, .nav-link, .page-link {
  min-height: 48px;
  min-width: 48px;
  /* Use padding to achieve size without changing visual appearance */
}
```

### Mobile Navigation
```html
<button class="hamburger" aria-label="Menu" aria-expanded="false">
  <span class="hamburger-line"></span>
  <span class="hamburger-line"></span>
  <span class="hamburger-line"></span>
</button>

<nav class="mobile-nav" aria-hidden="true">
  <!-- Full-screen overlay with large, spaced nav items -->
</nav>
```

Animation: Lines morph to X, nav slides in from right or fades in.

### Mobile Typography
```css
@media (max-width: 767px) {
  body {
    font-size: 17px;  /* Larger for thumb-held distance */
    line-height: 1.75;
  }
  h1 { font-size: 1.75rem; }
  h2 { font-size: 1.35rem; }
}
```

### Mobile Animation Adaptations
- Shorter durations (0.3s instead of 0.6s)
- Simpler effects (fade only, no complex transforms)
- Fewer animated elements (performance)
- Disable particle effects if present

```css
@media (max-width: 767px) {
  .animate-in {
    animation-duration: 0.3s;
  }
  .background-particles {
    display: none; /* Too heavy for mobile */
  }
}
```

### Touch Feedback
```css
/* Tap highlight */
.btn, .card {
  -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(57, 255, 20, 0.2);
}

/* Active state for touch */
.btn:active, .card:active {
  transform: scale(0.98);
  opacity: 0.9;
}

/* Remove 300ms tap delay */
* {
  touch-action: manipulation;
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] All touch targets are minimum 48x48px
- [ ] Mobile navigation works smoothly (hamburger menu)
- [ ] Typography is optimized for mobile reading
- [ ] Animations are simpler/faster on mobile
- [ ] Touch feedback is present (tap highlights, active states)
- [ ] No 300ms tap delay
- [ ] Tested on real devices (iPhone SE, iPhone 14 Pro Max, Android)
- [ ] Performance is 60fps on mid-range mobile devices

## Dependencies

- **Depends on**: Phase 1 (typography foundation must be done first)
- **Can run parallel to**: Phases 2-4 (mobile work is somewhat independent)
- **Blocks**: Phase 6 (real device testing is part of final QA)

## Considerations for Future Work

- Consider bottom navigation bar for very frequent actions
- Safe area insets for notched devices: env(safe-area-inset-*)
- Test with actual fingers, not just responsive mode
- Mobile-specific gestures (swipe to navigate) are P3—complex and may conflict with browser

# Task: Style Footer with Dark Theme

## What
Redesign the footer to match the hacker theme with dark surface background and muted text.

## Why
- Visual consistency with header
- Professional closure to pages
- Contains important links (LinkedIn, email)
- Should be subtle, not attention-grabbing

## Design Specification

### Visual
```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔│
│            © 2026 Milosz Czajkowski                     │
│       Built with Jekyll • Hosted on GitHub Pages        │
│               LinkedIn • Email                          │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
Background: #161b22 (surface)
Text: #8b949e (muted)
Links: #00ffff (cyan) → #ff00ff (magenta) on hover
Border: #30363d (1px top)
```

### Content
- Copyright with dynamic year
- Tech credits (Jekyll + GitHub Pages)
- Social links (LinkedIn, Email)

## Implementation

### CSS
```scss
.site-footer {
  background-color: var(--bg-surface);
  border-top: 1px solid var(--border-color);
  padding: 2rem 0;
  margin-top: 3rem;
  text-align: center;

  p {
    color: var(--text-muted);
    margin: 0.5rem 0;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
  }

  a {
    color: var(--color-secondary);
    text-decoration: none;
    transition: color var(--transition-fast);

    &:hover {
      color: var(--color-hover);
    }
  }
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Footer has dark surface background
- [ ] Top border separates from content
- [ ] Text is muted gray
- [ ] Links are cyan with magenta hover
- [ ] Content is centered
- [ ] Spacing feels balanced

# Task: Implement Card Component with Hover States

## Overview

Create a reusable card component for service cards, content blocks, and any elevated surface. Cards should have clear visual hierarchy and satisfying hover interactions.

## Background

Cards are the primary container for grouped content. In world-class interfaces:
- Cards are clearly elevated from background
- Hover states provide feedback and delight
- Cards feel "touchable" or "liftable"
- Consistent styling across all card types

## Implementation Details

### Card Base Styles

```css
.card {
  background: var(--bg-elevated);
  border: 1px solid var(--border-color);
  border-radius: 8px;
  padding: var(--space-6); /* 32px */
  box-shadow: var(--shadow-card);
  transition: 
    transform 0.2s cubic-bezier(0.4, 0, 0.2, 1),
    box-shadow 0.2s cubic-bezier(0.4, 0, 0.2, 1),
    border-color 0.2s ease;
}

@media (max-width: 767px) {
  .card {
    padding: var(--space-5); /* 24px */
    border-radius: 6px;
  }
}
```

### Card Hover State

```css
.card:hover {
  transform: translateY(-4px);
  border-color: rgba(57, 255, 20, 0.4);
  box-shadow: var(--shadow-card-hover);
}

/* For cards that are links */
a.card:hover {
  text-decoration: none;
}

/* Active/pressed state */
.card:active {
  transform: translateY(-2px);
  box-shadow: var(--shadow-md);
}
```

### Card Variants

```css
/* Feature card (larger, more prominent) */
.card--feature {
  padding: var(--space-8);
  border-radius: 12px;
}

/* Compact card */
.card--compact {
  padding: var(--space-4);
}

/* Card with accent border */
.card--accent {
  border-left: 3px solid var(--color-primary);
}
```

### Apply to Services Page

The services.md page should use card styling for each service tier:
- Wrap each service in a .card div
- Add appropriate hover states
- Consider grid layout for desktop (3 columns)

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] .card class defined with proper styling
- [ ] Hover state lifts card and increases shadow
- [ ] Border glows subtly on hover
- [ ] Transition is smooth (no jank)
- [ ] Mobile version has appropriate padding
- [ ] Card variants available (feature, compact, accent)
- [ ] Services page uses card styling

## Files to Modify

- `assets/css/style.scss` - Add card component styles
- `services.md` - May need HTML restructuring for cards

## Testing

- Hover interactions feel smooth and responsive
- Cards are clearly elevated from background
- Mobile touch states work (no hover dependency)

# Task: Refine Typography Scale and Rhythm

## Overview

Create a refined, systematic typography scale that serves as the foundation for the entire visual design. This isn't just "making fonts bigger"—it's establishing a coherent system with optical adjustments.

## Background

World-class typography has:
- **Modular scale**: Each size is mathematically related to others
- **Optical adjustments**: Larger text needs tighter tracking, smaller needs looser
- **Clear hierarchy**: Instant visual distinction between levels
- **Appropriate weight distribution**: Not everything bold, not everything light

## Implementation Details

### Typography Scale (Desktop)

```css
:root {
  /* Type scale - using 1.25 ratio (Major Third) */
  --font-size-xs: 0.8rem;      /* 12.8px - captions, meta */
  --font-size-sm: 0.9rem;      /* 14.4px - small text */
  --font-size-base: 1rem;      /* 16px - body */
  --font-size-md: 1.125rem;    /* 18px - lead text */
  --font-size-lg: 1.25rem;     /* 20px - H4 */
  --font-size-xl: 1.5rem;      /* 24px - H3 */
  --font-size-2xl: 1.75rem;    /* 28px - H2 */
  --font-size-3xl: 2rem;       /* 32px - H1 */
  --font-size-4xl: 2.5rem;     /* 40px - Display */
  --font-size-5xl: 3.5rem;     /* 56px - Hero */

  /* Tracking (letter-spacing) - tighter for large, looser for small */
  --tracking-tight: -0.02em;
  --tracking-normal: 0;
  --tracking-wide: 0.02em;
  --tracking-wider: 0.05em;

  /* Line heights */
  --leading-tight: 1.1;
  --leading-snug: 1.3;
  --leading-normal: 1.5;
  --leading-relaxed: 1.7;
}
```

### Apply to Elements

```css
h1 {
  font-size: var(--font-size-3xl);
  letter-spacing: var(--tracking-tight);
  line-height: var(--leading-tight);
}

h2 {
  font-size: var(--font-size-2xl);
  letter-spacing: var(--tracking-tight);
  line-height: var(--leading-snug);
}

body {
  font-size: var(--font-size-base);
  letter-spacing: var(--tracking-normal);
  line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);
}

.display-text, .hero-headline {
  font-size: var(--font-size-5xl);
  letter-spacing: var(--tracking-tight);
  line-height: var(--leading-tight);
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] CSS custom properties defined for all type sizes
- [ ] Tracking values applied appropriately per size
- [ ] Line heights are harmonious
- [ ] Headings have clear visual hierarchy
- [ ] Body text is highly readable
- [ ] Scale documented in CSS comments

## Files to Modify

- `assets/css/style.scss` - Add typography tokens and apply them

## Testing

- View all pages and verify hierarchy is clear
- Check line lengths don't exceed ~75 characters
- Verify readability at normal viewing distance

# Task: Add Touch-Specific Feedback Styles

## Overview

Add visual feedback for touch interactions—tap highlights, active states, and touch-action optimizations—to make mobile interactions feel responsive and intentional.

## Background

Touch feedback is critical because:
- No hover state on touch devices
- Users need confirmation their tap registered
- Makes interface feel responsive
- Prevents "did I tap it?" confusion

## Implementation Details

### Remove 300ms Tap Delay

```css
/* Apply to all interactive elements */
a, button, input, select, textarea, [role="button"] {
  touch-action: manipulation;
}

/* Or apply globally */
* {
  touch-action: manipulation;
}
```

### Tap Highlight Color

```css
/* Custom tap highlight (replaces browser default) */
a, button, .card, [role="button"] {
  -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(57, 255, 20, 0.15);
}

/* Or disable default and use custom active state */
.btn {
  -webkit-tap-highlight-color: transparent;
}
```

### Active States for Touch

```css
@media (max-width: 767px) {
  /* Button active state */
  .btn:active {
    transform: scale(0.97);
    opacity: 0.9;
    transition-duration: 0.1s;
  }

  /* Card active state */
  .card:active {
    transform: scale(0.98);
    box-shadow: var(--shadow-sm);
  }

  /* Link active state */
  a:active {
    opacity: 0.7;
  }

  /* Nav link active state */
  .page-link:active, .nav-link:active {
    background: rgba(57, 255, 20, 0.1);
    border-radius: 4px;
  }
}
```

### Touch Feedback Animation

```css
/* Ripple-like feedback (optional, more complex) */
.touch-feedback {
  position: relative;
  overflow: hidden;
}

.touch-feedback::after {
  content: '';
  position: absolute;
  inset: 0;
  background: radial-gradient(circle, rgba(57, 255, 20, 0.2) 0%, transparent 70%);
  opacity: 0;
  transform: scale(0);
  transition: opacity 0.3s, transform 0.3s;
}

.touch-feedback:active::after {
  opacity: 1;
  transform: scale(2);
  transition-duration: 0.1s;
}
```

### Form Element Touch States

```css
@media (max-width: 767px) {
  input:focus, textarea:focus, select:focus {
    outline: 2px solid var(--color-primary);
    outline-offset: 2px;
  }

  /* Larger touch area for checkboxes/radio */
  input[type="checkbox"],
  input[type="radio"] {
    width: 24px;
    height: 24px;
  }
}
```

### Prevent Accidental Actions

```css
/* Prevent text selection on tap */
.btn, .card, .nav-link {
  -webkit-user-select: none;
  user-select: none;
}

/* But allow in content areas */
.page-content p, .page-content li {
  -webkit-user-select: text;
  user-select: text;
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] No 300ms tap delay
- [ ] Custom tap highlight color matches theme
- [ ] Active states provide clear feedback
- [ ] Buttons/cards visually respond to touch
- [ ] Form elements have clear focus states
- [ ] No accidental text selection on buttons
- [ ] Feedback feels immediate and responsive

## Files to Modify

- `assets/css/style.scss` - Touch feedback styles

## Testing

- Test on actual touch device
- Tap all interactive elements
- Verify feedback is visible
- Check no lag between tap and visual response

# Task: Define CSS Custom Properties

## What
Create the CSS variable system that defines the entire color palette and typography references.

## Why
- Single source of truth for all colors
- Easy to tweak and maintain
- Enables potential future theming
- Industry best practice for design systems

## Implementation

### In assets/css/style.scss
```scss
---
---

// CSS Custom Properties (must be before @import to override Minima)
:root {
  // Backgrounds
  --bg-primary: #0d1117;
  --bg-surface: #161b22;

  // Accent colors
  --color-primary: #39ff14;    // Neon green
  --color-secondary: #00ffff;  // Cyan
  --color-hover: #ff00ff;      // Magenta
  --color-warning: #ff8c00;    // Orange

  // Text colors
  --text-primary: #c9d1d9;
  --text-muted: #8b949e;

  // Borders
  --border-color: #30363d;

  // Typography
  --font-heading: 'Share Tech Mono', monospace;
  --font-body: 'Fira Code', monospace;

  // Transitions
  --transition-fast: 0.2s ease;
  --transition-normal: 0.3s ease;

  // Spacing
  --content-max-width: 800px;
  --spacing-unit: 1rem;
}

@import "minima";

// Base overrides
html {
  background-color: var(--bg-primary);
}

body {
  background-color: var(--bg-primary);
  color: var(--text-primary);
  font-family: var(--font-body);
  line-height: 1.6;
}
```

## Color Reference Table
| Variable | Hex | Visual |
|----------|-----|--------|
| --bg-primary | #0d1117 | Dark charcoal (GitHub dark) |
| --bg-surface | #161b22 | Slightly lighter dark |
| --color-primary | #39ff14 | Neon green (Matrix-style) |
| --color-secondary | #00ffff | Cyan (terminal accent) |
| --color-hover | #ff00ff | Magenta (synthwave) |
| --color-warning | #ff8c00 | Orange (badges) |
| --text-primary | #c9d1d9 | Light gray (readable) |
| --text-muted | #8b949e | Medium gray (secondary) |
| --border-color | #30363d | Dark gray (subtle) |

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] All variables defined in :root
- [ ] Body background is dark
- [ ] Body text is light gray
- [ ] Variables use semantic names
- [ ] Comments explain each variable group

# Epic: Theme Foundation - Colors & Typography

## Overview
Establish the core CSS foundation that all other styling builds upon. This includes CSS custom properties (variables) for the color palette and typography setup with Google Fonts.

## Why This Comes First
- All component styling references these variables
- Changing colors later only requires editing variables
- Typography must load before content renders
- Foundation errors cascade to everything else

## Technical Approach

### CSS Custom Properties
Define in `:root` for global access:
```css
:root {
  /* Backgrounds */
  --bg-primary: #0d1117;
  --bg-surface: #161b22;

  /* Accents */
  --color-primary: #39ff14;    /* Neon green */
  --color-secondary: #00ffff;  /* Cyan */
  --color-hover: #ff00ff;      /* Magenta */
  --color-warning: #ff8c00;    /* Orange */

  /* Text */
  --text-primary: #c9d1d9;
  --text-muted: #8b949e;

  /* Borders */
  --border-color: #30363d;

  /* Typography */
  --font-heading: 'Share Tech Mono', monospace;
  --font-body: 'Fira Code', monospace;
}
```

### Google Fonts Integration
Add to default.html head:
```html
<link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com">
<link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.gstatic.com" crossorigin>
<link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Fira+Code:wght@400;500;600&family=Share+Tech+Mono&display=swap" rel="stylesheet">
```

### Base Reset
```css
html, body {
  background-color: var(--bg-primary);
  color: var(--text-primary);
  font-family: var(--font-body);
}
```

## Files to Modify
- `_layouts/default.html` - Add font links
- `assets/css/style.scss` - Add variables and base styles

## Success Criteria
- [ ] CSS variables defined and accessible
- [ ] Fonts loading correctly
- [ ] Body background is dark (#0d1117)
- [ ] Body text is light gray (#c9d1d9)
- [ ] Monospace font applied throughout

## Blocks
All component styling tasks depend on this.

# Task: Optimize Mobile Typography

## Overview

Mobile typography needs specific optimization—it's not just "smaller desktop." Users hold phones closer to their face, use them in varied lighting, and scroll with their thumbs. Typography must adapt.

## Background

Mobile reading is fundamentally different:
- Closer viewing distance (compensate with slightly larger text)
- Single-column layouts (shorter line lengths automatically)
- Variable lighting conditions (need good contrast)
- Thumb scrolling (comfortable text size for quick scanning)

iOS and Android both recommend larger base sizes for mobile than most designers use.

## Implementation Details

### Mobile Type Scale

```css
@media (max-width: 767px) {
  :root {
    /* Increase base size for mobile */
    --font-size-base: 1.0625rem; /* 17px instead of 16px */

    /* Scale down headings more aggressively */
    --font-size-5xl: 2rem;     /* 32px - Hero (was 56px) */
    --font-size-4xl: 1.75rem;  /* 28px - Display (was 40px) */
    --font-size-3xl: 1.5rem;   /* 24px - H1 (was 32px) */
    --font-size-2xl: 1.25rem;  /* 20px - H2 (was 28px) */
    --font-size-xl: 1.125rem;  /* 18px - H3 (was 24px) */
  }

  body {
    font-size: var(--font-size-base);
    line-height: 1.7; /* Slightly more line height for scanning */
  }

  h1 {
    font-size: var(--font-size-3xl);
    /* Keep tight line height for impact */
    line-height: 1.2;
  }

  h2 {
    font-size: var(--font-size-2xl);
    line-height: 1.3;
  }

  /* Ensure max line length */
  p, li {
    max-width: 75ch; /* Approximately 75 characters */
  }
}
```

### Adjustments for Small Screens

```css
@media (max-width: 375px) {
  :root {
    /* Further reduce for iPhone SE etc. */
    --font-size-5xl: 1.75rem;
    --font-size-4xl: 1.5rem;
    --font-size-3xl: 1.35rem;
  }
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Base font size is 17px on mobile
- [ ] Headings scale down appropriately (not just shrunk desktop)
- [ ] Line height is slightly increased (1.7 vs 1.5)
- [ ] Line length stays within 75 characters
- [ ] Text is easily readable on iPhone SE (small)
- [ ] Text is appropriate on iPhone 14 Pro Max (large)
- [ ] Passes squint test (can skim at arm's length)

## Files to Modify

- `assets/css/style.scss` - Add mobile-specific typography rules

## Testing

- Test on actual devices if possible
- Use Chrome DevTools device emulation as minimum
- Test with "reader distance" (arm's length)
- Verify line length doesn't get too long on tablets

# Task: Add Subtle Animated Background Effects

## Overview

Create atmospheric background effects for the hero section—gradient orbs, subtle particles, or animated glow—that create depth and visual interest without overwhelming the content.

## Background

Background effects create atmosphere:
