# Overview

Bring the interface to life with purposeful motion. This phase adds scroll-triggered animations, hover effects, staggered entrances, and microinteractions that make every interaction feel responsive and delightful.

## Background & Justification

Motion is what separates good interfaces from great ones. Stripe's scroll animations, Linear's hover states, and Vercel's staggered reveals all share:
- Purposeful motion that communicates (not decorative)
- Physics-based easing (ease-out for entrances, ease-in for exits)
- Staggered timing that creates visual rhythm
- Respect for user preferences (prefers-reduced-motion)

Current state: The site is static except for the cursor blink. No scroll animations, no hover lifts, no entrance effects. Interactions feel flat.

## Goals

1. Implement scroll-triggered fade-up animations using Intersection Observer
2. Add hover lift effects to all interactive elements (cards, buttons, links)
3. Create staggered entrance animations for lists and card grids
4. Add button microinteractions (lift on hover, press on active)
5. Animate nav underlines (grow from center)

## Technical Approach

### Scroll-Triggered Animations
```javascript
// Intersection Observer setup
const observer = new IntersectionObserver((entries) => {
  entries.forEach(entry => {
    if (entry.isIntersecting) {
      entry.target.classList.add('animate-in');
    }
  });
}, { threshold: 0.2 });
```

### Entrance Animation (fadeUp)
```css
@keyframes fadeUp {
  from {
    opacity: 0;
    transform: translateY(20px);
  }
  to {
    opacity: 1;
    transform: translateY(0);
  }
}

.animate-in {
  animation: fadeUp 0.6s cubic-bezier(0.4, 0, 0.2, 1) forwards;
}
```

### Staggered Timing
```css
.stagger-children > *:nth-child(1) { animation-delay: 0s; }
.stagger-children > *:nth-child(2) { animation-delay: 0.1s; }
.stagger-children > *:nth-child(3) { animation-delay: 0.2s; }
/* etc. */
```

### Hover Effects
```css
/* Card/Button lift */
.card, .btn {
  transition: all 0.2s cubic-bezier(0.4, 0, 0.2, 1);
}
.card:hover, .btn:hover {
  transform: translateY(-4px);
  box-shadow: var(--shadow-lg);
}
.btn:active {
  transform: translateY(1px);
  box-shadow: var(--shadow-sm);
}

/* Link underline grow */
.nav-link {
  background: linear-gradient(currentColor, currentColor) no-repeat center bottom / 0% 2px;
  transition: background-size 0.3s ease-out;
}
.nav-link:hover {
  background-size: 100% 2px;
}
```

### Reduced Motion Support
```css
@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
  *, *::before, *::after {
    animation-duration: 0.01ms !important;
    transition-duration: 0.01ms !important;
  }
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Sections fade up as they enter viewport
- [ ] Cards lift on hover with shadow increase
- [ ] Buttons have hover lift and active press states
- [ ] List items animate in with stagger timing
- [ ] Nav links have animated underlines
- [ ] All animations respect prefers-reduced-motion
- [ ] 60fps maintained on mid-range devices
- [ ] No layout shift during animations (CLS = 0)

## Dependencies

- **Depends on**: Phase 2 (surfaces/cards must exist to animate them)
- **Blocks**: Phase 4 (hero animations build on this system)

## Considerations for Future Work

- Keep JS minimal—one small file for Intersection Observer
- Use will-change sparingly (only where needed)
- Test on real devices, not just dev tools throttling
- Animation library not needed—vanilla CSS/JS sufficient
- Consider adding a "motion scale" CSS property for easy tuning

